5":"1305","1238":"1238","1303":"1303","1259":"1259","1269":"1269","1233":"1233","1298":"1298","about 1269":"circa 1269","1308":"1308","Burton upon Trent, Staffordshire, England":"Burton upon Trent, Staffordshire, England","Atcham, Shropshire, England":"Atcham, Shropshire, England","Sufton Court, Mordiford, Herefordshire, England":"Sufton Court, Herefordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England":"England"},"en":{"1238–1303":"1238–1303","1233–1305":"1233–1305","1233–1308":"1233–1308","1269–1298":"1269–1298","1206–1263":"1206–1263","1263":"1263","1290":"1290","Abt 1263":"about 1263","1206":"1206","1305":"1305","1238":"1238","1303":"1303","1259":"1259","1269":"1269","1233":"1233","1298":"1298","about 1269":"about 1269","1308":"1308","Burton upon Trent, Staffordshire, England":"Burton upon Trent, Staffordshire, England","Atcham, Shropshire, England":"Atcham, Shropshire, England","Sufton Court, Mordiford, Herefordshire, England":"Sufton Court, Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Hereford","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Hertford (Hertfordshire) (in which the <i>t</i> was lost early, as in the modern pronunciation <i>Harford</i>), Hereford (Herefordshire), or Harford (Devon, Gloucestershire). The Devon and Herefordshire placenames derive from Old English <i>here</i> ‘army’ + <i>ford</i> ‘ford’, while the Gloucestershire and Hertfordshire placenames derive from Old English <i>heorot</i> ‘hart, stag’ + <i>ford</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Herford","meanings":["English: variant of   Hereford  .","German: variant of   Herfurth  .","German: habitational name from a place of that name in Westphalia."]},{"name":"Heryford","meanings":["Altered form of English   Hereford  ."]},{"name":"Heriford","meanings":["Altered form of English   Hereford  ."]},{"name":"Harford","meanings":["English (Wiltshire and Gloucestershire): variant of   Hereford  ."]},{"name":"Havard","meanings":["English and Welsh (Brecknockshire and Glamorgan): habitational name from Haverfordwest (Pembrokeshire), from Old English <i>hæfer</i> ‘goat’ + <i>ford</i> ‘ford’.","English and Welsh (Brecknockshire and Glamorgan): in some cases, the name may also be a variant of   Hereford  .","French: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Hahward</i>, composed of the elements <i>hah</i>, which is unexplained, and <i>ward</i> ‘guard’."]},{"name":"Hurford","meanings":["English (Devon and Somerset): variant of   Hereford  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":21,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":52,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Robert de Hereford was born in 1238, in Atcham, Shropshire, England as the son of Roger de Hereford I. He married Johanna Brampton about 1269. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in 1303, in Burton upon Trent, Staffordshire, England, at the age of 65."},"et":{"1238–1303":"1238–1303","1233–1305":"1233–1305","1233–1308":"1233–1308","1269–1298":"1269–1298","1206–1263":"1206–1263","1263":"1263","1290":"1290","Abt 1263":"umbes 1263","1206":"1206","1305":"1305","1238":"1238","1303":"1303","1259":"1259","1269":"1269","1233":"1233","1298":"1298","about 1269":"umbes 1269","1308":"1308","Burton upon Trent, Staffordshire, England":"Burton upon Trent, Staffordshire, England","Atcham, Shropshire, England":"Atcham, Shropshire, England","Sufton Court, Mordiford, Herefordshire, England":"Sufton Court, Herefordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England"},"fi":{"1238–1303":"1238–1303","1233–1305":"1233–1305","1233–1308":"1233–1308","1269–1298":"1269–1298","1206–1263":"1206–1263","1263":"1263","1290":"1290","Abt 1263":"noin 1263","1206":"1206","1305":"1305","1238":"1238"